The same, whether as one wavering in faith or straying from the faith and the fixed judgment of the catholic church, did practice in his own person, contrary to such faith and fixed judg- ment, divination or incantations after this manner, to wit, on the eve or on the day of the feast of St. Matthew the apostle, in the year of our Lord 1439,² at Ingarsby,⁸ he took to himself a boy, Maurice by name, and, observing a damnable superstition, smeared the boy's thumb-nail, bidding him look upon his nail and discover to him what sort of things he saw there, and, reading or saying his charms the while, asked of the same boy what he had seen, incurring the sentence of the greater excom- munication passed against such persons in general ; and knowing himself to be thus excommunicate, has since then celebrated masses, even in solemrli wise4, and otherwise has taken part in divine service, incurring irre u arit .
